text:
Tomorrow morning we have a leadership election to replace Liz Cheney. The two contestants are:

Chip Roy of Texas, a Freedom Caucus member who is among the most conservative members of Congress. His lifetime score from Heritage Action is 96%, one of the very highest in Congress. According to the website 538, Chip voted with Trump in Congress 90% of the time.

Elise Stefanik of New York. Elise is among the most liberal Republicans in Congress. Her lifetime score from Heritage action is 48% making her the 6th lowest out of approximately 200 Republicans. According to the website 538, she voted with Trump only 78% of the time.

Trump has endorsed Stefanik for Republican Conference Chair and said Roy will lose his seat in a primary, because Roy voted to certify the election.

Who would you support for Republican Conference Chair?

text:
I am heartbroken by the escalating tensions and growing violence in Israel and the Palestinian territories. I believe we must pursue a permanent diplomatic solution to this decades-long conflict. It is important that all parties take steps that move them closer to a permanent two-state solution that preserves the self-determination and dignity of both peoples.

I am deeply committed to the strong relationship between Israel and the United States and believe that Israel must be able to defend itself. I have long been a supporter of the Iron Dome program and the importance of this program was underscored this week by its successful interception of incoming rockets launched by Hamas. These attacks by Hamas must cease as they are causing more death among countless civilian lives and deepening the devastation for Israelis and Palestinians alike.

We must also not forget that the goal of Israel as a Jewish Democratic state is not incompatible with respecting human rights and creating communities where Palestinians can feel safe in their home.

I urge the Biden Administration to pursue all efforts to broker a ceasefire as soon as possible. All parties must take steps to de-escalate the situation and preserve human life.

text:
VACCINATION UPDATE
Starting today (Thursday May 13th) the FEMA run Center City Vaccination Center (CCVC) will begin administering Pfizer dose 1 to Philadelphia adolescents ages 12-15. This decision was made by the Philadelphia Department of Public Health following the guidance of the CDC.

COVID-19 vaccines are free and available to anyone who works, resides, or goes to school in Philadelphia. Immigration status is not a factor in vaccine eligibility. Adolescents ages 12-15 who wish to get vaccinated must be accompanied by a parent or guardian. Proof of age is required to receive the vaccine. Acceptable forms of age identification include:

‚Ä¢Access school or health care portals via phone
‚Ä¢Copy of school or sports health forms
‚Ä¢Insurance Cards
‚Ä¢Passports
‚Ä¢Birth certificates or photos of their birth certificate
‚Ä¢Any other documents with the child's name and date of birth.

FEMA‚Äôs Center City Vaccination Center (CCVC), located at the Pennsylvania Convention Center, will administer the Pfizer vaccine to those over the age of 12 and the Johnson & Johnson vaccine to those over the age of 18. This site accepts a mixture of appointments and walk-ups. Walk-ups are welcome from 8am-5pm. For more information on CCVC hours of operation, appointment information, and what to expect, please visit:

https://www.phila.gov/2021-03-02-getting-vaccinated-at-the-center-city-vaccination-center-what-you-need-to-know/

PHILA.GOV
Getting vaccinated at the Center City Vaccination Center: What you need to know | Department of Public Health

text:
America‚Äôs police officers deserve our respect and admiration.

Every day, law enforcement professionals lace up their boots and don the badge knowing this day could be their last. They know that just one call gone wrong or one split-second decision during a traffic stop could mean the difference between returning home to see their family or never coming home again.

Still, they show up every day. They don‚Äôt do it for the money or the fame. They live to protect and serve, to keep our communities and families safe. They put in countless hours, long shifts, endure endless abuse from the folks they‚Äôre trying to help, and they do it all with love, dedication, and passion for the work they do.

It‚Äôs a thankless job. More often than not, police officers are meeting people on their absolute worst day. Whether they‚Äôre handing out a speeding ticket to a reckless driver putting others at risk or trying to talk down a drug addict hanging on by a thread, they approach every situation looking to help, even when the odds seemed stacked against them. America‚Äôs police officers routinely go above and beyond to live up to their mission‚Äîto protect and serve.

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm proud to stand up and honor all our police officers during National Police Week. At a time when America‚Äôs law enforcement officers are facing unprecedented attacks in the media and from liberal politicians, they need our support. The notion of ‚Äúdefunding the police,‚Äù as some have called for, is absurd and repugnant. We should reject it at every turn.

It doesn‚Äôt even make sense. We don‚Äôt ‚Äúdefund‚Äù roadways because there‚Äôs potholes. We don‚Äôt ‚Äúdefund‚Äù schools because our children aren‚Äôt learning enough. Instead of defunding the police, local communities should be investing in law enforcement. They should be investing in better training, investing in better tools, and investing in our officers. We should be backing the blue and supporting those that protect and serve.

We, as Americans, should all have their back. After all, they‚Äôre the ones out there putting their lives on the line to keep us and our families safe. We depend on the men and women in law enforcement, and they should be able to depend on us.

Wisconsin's rural communities rely on the USPS, but over the past year they've been dealing with historic mail delays and lost packages. Now with his new 10-year plan, Postmaster General DeJoy is doubling down on this poor service - raising prices, slowing delivery, and reducing access to post offices.

Wisconsinites deserve better. I'm calling on Postmaster General DeJoy to reevaluate this 10-year plan to make sure our rural communities have consistent, affordable, and timely access to postal services. text:
South Carolinians continue to rely on federal disaster relief funds to aid in recovery efforts from our many storms and floods. When Congress appropriates disaster funding, we need to be sure that these funds are being allocated properly and timely. For those who need assistance, every day counts, but the disaster grant process can take years.

To increase government accountability in the allocation of disaster relief funds, I introduced the Disaster Relief Transparency Act alongside Congresswoman Nancy Mace Congressman Carlos A. Gimenez and Congressman Buddy Carter.

The Disaster Relief Transparency Act will keep the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development and FEMA Federal Emergency Management Agency accountable to the taxpayers. This legislation ensures the agencies are acting in good faith to deliver disaster funds to the places that have demonstrated a need for help. We must improve the consistency, timeliness, and reporting methods of funding allocations to ensure South Carolina receives every dollar of rightfully owed disaster relief funding.
Read more: https://rice.house.gov/press-releases?ID=1A2C45D6-95A6-4555-80B5-602D06F5AE58

RICE.HOUSE.GOV
Congressman Rice Introduces Disaster Relief Transparency Act

text:
Today, the House will vote on H.R.2547, the Comprehensive Debt Collection Improvement Act, legislation I support which would provide important protections for small businesses, servicemembers, students, and other consumers against mistreatment and harassment by certain debt collectors.

During the pandemic, many consumers and small businesses have struggled to keep up with their bills--through no fault of their own--while debt collectors have seen record profits. Meanwhile, recent Consumer Financial Protection Bureau reporting reveals that its consumer complaint database received 82,700 consumer complaints regarding debt collection issues in 2020, a 10% increase from the previous year. In addition, research has shown that that abusive debt collection practices disproportionately harm communities of color and low-income communities.

Reform of our debt collection laws is long overdue, and this legislation is a great first step. I plan to vote to pass it and send it to the Senate, who should not hesitate to bring it to a vote.

https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamminsky/2021/05/11/democrats-overhaul-debt-collection-laws-and-discharge-private-student-loans/?sh=3c5164f676df

FORBES.COM
Democrats: Overhaul Debt Collection Laws And Discharge Private Student Loans

text:
Back in 2018, I invited VICE News to join me as I prepared to grill the wholesalers about their role in the opioid crisis ravaging across West Virginia.

Fast forward to 2021 and West Virginia is still dealing with an overdose epidemic. Drug distributors played a major role in fueling the opioid epidemic and did nothing to stop it from growing out of control. They need to be held accountable.

With this trial in West Virginia and the thousands of others around the country they will be held financially accountable for the damage they have already done. Earlier this year I introduced the Opioid Settlement Accountability Act which would ensure the funds that states receive from opioid settlements are put towards opioid treatment, prevention, education, and enforcement. Then yesterday the House passed the Block, Report, And Suspend Suspicious Shipments Act which will help hold them accountable to ensure pill dumping won‚Äôt happen in the future.

https://www.vice.com/en/article/59qbpa/this-republican-is-going-after-big-pharma-for-the-opioid-crisis-ravaging-his-state

text:
The It's In DeKalb County Human Services Department announces the beginning of its 2021-2022 Human Services Grant Cycle.

The purpose of the Human Services Grant Program is to provide opportunities for community partnership with local organizations that can successfully address identified service needs for the citizens of DeKalb County, Georgia.

Eligible non-profit organizations are encouraged to apply for the opportunity to be awarded a grant utilizing County General Fund and Victim Assistance funds.

Agencies that receive Victim Assistance grant funds, must meet the County‚Äôs eligibility criteria and must also be certified to provide victim assistance programming through the State of Georgia Criminal Justice Coordinating Council.

The Human Services Grant Program is competitive, and the total amount of awards allotted each year is based on the availability of funds. This grant program is designed to supplement existing programs and activities for DeKalb County residents.

Examples of appropriate service areas for the Human Service Grant Program include, but are not limited to, youth development/early childhood programs, senior services, services for individuals with disabilities & special needs, domestic violence & family intervention, substance abuse treatment & prevention, mental & behavioral health, health & wellness, nutrition & hunger prevention, legal counseling & advocacy, family economics & money management, refugee services, homelessness and family transition.

A Virtual Public Information Meeting scheduled for Wednesday, May 19, 2021 at 10:00 a.m. will provide the specifics regarding the Human Services Grant application process.

For more information, call Ms. Lisa Thomas, Grants Coordinator at 470-543-0754 in the DeKalb County Human Services Department.

For information on obtaining Victim Assistance Program Certification, contact the State of Georgia Criminal Justice Coordinating Council at 404-657-1956.

DEKALBCOUNTYGA.ZOOM.US
Welcome! You are invited to join a webinar: 2021-2022 Human Services Grant Virtual Public Information Meeting. After registering, you will receive a confirmation email about joining the webinar.

This week is National Police Week (May 9-15, 2021).

It is an honor to be an original cosponsor of H.R. 386, recognizing National Police Week and remembering our law enforcement members who have made the ultimate sacrifice in order to defend their communities from violence and crime. It honors the 394 officers killed in the line of duty in 2020, including EPC Sheriff's Office Deputy, Jeff Hopkins. The resolution expresses steadfast support and appreciation for law enforcement and gratitude for the thin blue line.

Thank you to my colleagues in Congress, Representatives Congressman Michael Guest, and Congresswoman Julia Letlow for sponsoring this important and meaningful resolution.

You can view the names of the brave heroes who made the ultimate sacrifice from your state here: https://nleomf.org/facts-figures/2021-roll-call-of-heroes.

Teller County Sheriff's Office
Colorado Springs Police Department
